text:
We played this game at a party with a bunch of adults and were hooked! It's fabulous for all ages! Adults will take it a little more seriously and go for moves that you'll be amazed with. It's easy enough that younger kids can join in on the fun too. Great entertainment for the entire family and a huge hit at a games party!

It's important that you set up the base well otherwise your games will end quicker than you think because the entire "tower" will fall over due to the base failure. Think outside of the box when making your move. You'll often be surprised at what will keep "hanging in the balance" with this game!

title: I really like using this game for play therapy.
text: I've had this game in the office for three or four years now. I found it challenging to begin with and now, find it fairly easy, but still produce major crashes from time to time. The kids love it when I mess up! Most of the kids really like it. It challenges them to learn the rules (one hand only, you can't hang 2 pieces in the same spot) and helps deal with frustration tolerance and eye/hand coordination. It is too frustrating for some, but that still provides a learning experience and they get to help me with color ID (the blue and green spots on the die look alike to me).  I have noticed that the holes in the base have loosened up a lot over the years, so I may have to narrow them or drill some new holes. I like the one reviewer's suggestion of add-on pieces and different bases.  I am convinced this was invented by a couple of guys with a 12 pack and a bunch of wire coat hangers.

title: Brain-Building Creative Game
text: Over a year ago I picked this up for my always-busy son who simply cannot stop moving and learning. I think we have played it the "right" way maybe five times but it's been pulled out and enjoyed a thousand times over. I *LOVE* this game because it can be played alone and used like a one-of-a-kind building set. It has gotten so much use the plastic tube it came in fell apart so now it has it's very own storage bin. When other children come over, it is something new they have never seen and they each enjoy manipulating the pieces to get them to balance or dangle just right. My son makes "lightning rods" and "electrical lines" with them and occasionally electrocutes nearby building block towers, completely demolishing them. (Boys!) It is a very unique game that catches the interest of just about everyone who sees it - adults and children alike - and I owe this game many thanks for letting me get dinner cooked or a phone call made in pure, blissful silence!

title: Wish I hadn't given it as a gift....wish I had kept it for myself!
text:
Best Secret Santa gift ever! The lady I gave it to has played it with her children, whole family, elderly mother, and all of us at work. It's a game that both kids and adults can play at the same time and feel challenged. We did some variations to make things more difficult with older kids (like using your non-dominant hand only), and will be purchasing some for a children's program our office runs.

One of the best parts is that the variations are endless, whether the number of players, style of play, or how the game progresses. You are only limited by your creativity. And when it's all over, it easily packs up into a small container. In theory, it could be tossed in a big purse and taken to play anywhere.

Endless fun!

title: Worst gift I have ever bought on Amazon
text: I bought three of these as Christmas gifts and they are HORRIBLE. First, the die that needed to play the game is MISSING. So there's no way to roll the dice. Second, this game is made of metal rods which a child could easily fall and impale themselves, I am not exaggerating, I was a teacher for 20 years and I'm telling you, there are three long, straight steel rods that could maim or kill a child. I could see a small child sticking that right in their ear or in the nose as well. But beside that, this game is impossible to play. Even we ADULTS could not get the pieces to balance. Worst purchase ever. Since two of these were mailed gifts, I'll replace those with something that is FUN, COMPLETE, and SAFE. The third one we are stuck with here. A waste of $41 plus tax.  I'm keeping a copy of this review since it hasn't shown up on AMAZON as of yet. :(

title: Great entertainment!
text: This game was recommended to me by a friend recently, and I'm delighted that she told me about it.  Suspend is AWESOME!  It's a game of luck, skill, and fun.  The rules include three levels of play, but we also bent or changed rules, as well.  Basically, there is an easily-assembled stand, and players take turns balancing rods of different lengths and configurations from the hook at the top of the stand and from other suspended rods.  Four adults and an 11-year-old took turns playing for a number of hours over two days' time, and we not only enjoyed playing, when it was our turns, but also enjoyed watching others play.  We don't have many toys or forms of entertainment for our 11-year-old grandson, when he comes to visit, and this fit the ticket perfectly, but the adults enjoyed it as much as he did.  I am ordering more games to give as gifts.

title: Big Design Flaw that compromises long-term use
text:
What's the point of durability if you can't play the entire game after losing 1 little wooden dowel?

With other toys, it's not a big deal if a magnet tile or a tinker toy piece goes missing here or there. But I am not going to pay another $18 for a little wooden connector dowel to make this Melissa and Doug Suspend game playable again.

If the wooden connector goes missing, you can't play with ANY of the pieces as intended. It's ridiculous. And they have no listed options to purchase a replacement.

So yeah...this game was great for 10 minutes. Do NOT recommend.

title: A really fun game, although for only 1-4 players
text:
This game is a simple concept, and yet I really enjoy playing it. It takes a combination of strategy, dexterity, and balancing in order to be good at the game. And the whole tide can change with just one turn, which definitely adds to the fun in my opinion.

It also seems to be something that both the adults and the nieces/nephews on my family can all enjoy playing, so I wish that there were some sort of expansion set that would allow more than just 4 people to play.

Aside from that, I couldn't ask anything more, and I really wish I could give this 4.5 stars.

So if you don't mind playing with 4 players or less (or perhaps you might want to experiment with combining two sets), I say go for it!

title: A balancing Jenga-type dexterity game with funky metal rods
text:
COMPONENTS: I've always loved dexterity games, and this is a good one. My game came in a long cylindrical plastic tube which contained a wooden base and metal frame that takes you 10 seconds to put together each time you play, 24 metal rods with rubber tips in 6 colours, a colour die, and an instruction sheet.

SET-UP: First you assemble the wooden base with the four metal rods and wooden connector. Then the metal rods/pieces are shared out, each player getting the same number of each colour, and extras (if any) going to a draw pile.

GAME-PLAY: The basic objective is to be the first player who gets rid of all their rods/pieces, by hanging them from the structure, taking turns to place one at a time, depending on what colour you roll on the die. But there are some rules for placement: You can only use one hand when placing a piece. And once you let go and remove your hand - your turn is done. You can hang your piece anywhere, except on a notch or straight section already used by another piece. If after letting your piece go any other piece touches the ground, you need to reposition your piece. Finally, any pieces that fall during your turn, get added to your pile.

LOOKS: Suspend has quality components, and is an attention-grabber when set up on the table or in play. It's fun to play yourself, but also fun to watch others play.

ACCESSIBLE: The beauty about a game like this is that anybody of any age or ability can play it. The rules are easy to learn and understand, and you can be playing it 60 seconds after you've seen it for the first time. Plus an entire game can be played in well under 10 minutes.

DYNAMIC: Although Suspend shares something in common with Jenga at its raw level, the components have a very different look, and the way the balancing works is quite different. You are not working with a static tower, but the entire structure will move and change every time you play a piece. This makes it slightly less predictable and even harder to assess what will happen each time you add a piece, but it also makes it dynamic and exciting to watch and play.

FUN: Anything that involves physically building something and watching it tumble down will create moments of tension (will it fall?), moments of drama (will he succeed?), moments of disaster (oh, it toppled!). Moments like these that also create laughs and entertainment. The dynamic structure can create gasps as each piece is added and the entire structure swings and changes, and also moments of frustration when pieces tumble off or the entire thing falls over. It really is just a fun game!

VARIANTS: The game comes with a few ways to play, but what it really needs are some good house rules and official variations, which can mitigate the frustration that can be caused by rolling the die. Fortunately you'll find lots of good suggested house rules online that improve this, although for the average person this won't be an issue, given how quick and fun the game is.

RECOMMENDATION: The central element that makes Suspend so much fun is the tense battle against momentum and gravity as you carefully position a new piece onto a swaying and volatile structure! The entertainment that this provides makes it very worth while. There are some real strengths here in terms of accessibility and appeal, and the amount of fun that the game Suspend can produce for a wide range of people. For me Suspend is a keeper!

- BoardGameGeek reviewer EndersGame

title: Surprise hit with adults!
text:
I host a small adult game night at a local theater. I purchased Suspend last holiday season and nearly a year later, no one had played it yet. (To be fair, we have dozens upon dozens of games to choose from.) A few weeks ago I was contemplating taking it out of the group of games I haul back and forth each night we play, since the cylindrical shape doesn't pack easily. I figured I'd take the already-packed box of games for November's final game night, then select new games and repack without Suspend.

While one person was waiting for a game to join, he pulled out Suspend and started setting it up on the living room table, just to see what the game looked like. A card game ended and those players wandered into the room where Suspend was, and it was decided they'd all try and play a test game of it.

For the next hour and forty-five minutes, the Suspend players had several raucous rounds of games going, and by the end of the night, everyone else had gathered around and the room was filled with so much cheering and bantering that it rivaled watching a football game! It was enough fun that several people pulled out their phones to add Suspend to their shopping cart right then and there.

Most of the night was spent playing the basic games described in the rules, however we came up with some other game ideas to try another night, including turning it into a drinking game and also combining multiple sets and base points. One thing that contributed to the fun of the game was having it on a lower table that players could easily move around.

This was a surprise hit with the adults, who compared it to a modern sort of "Pick-up Sticks vs. Jenga" game. I DO think it might be very challenging for younger kids, though I myself was a pre-STEM kid who probably would have enjoyed this right along with the chemistry and robotics sets I had in 2nd-4th grade. I may not have been able to play this as a kid, or with my own kid as she grew up, but the adults who played this sure made my purchase feel worthwhile!

title: it's fun, but the kids didn't want to play it anymore after a few rounds...
text:
in a day and age when so many kids are addicted to electronic media, it's nice there are companies like melissa and doub who still whip out old-fashioned toys and games that require tactile interaction.

'suspend' is actually a pretty simple game in concept. each player receives the same group of six or seven pieces of varying lengths. you take turns hanging them from the grooves. it's kind of like jenga - the first person to hang his or her pieces wins. if you knock the thing over, you take all the pieces. the game also comes with a die to add a 'twister' like spin to it and make it a bit more complicated.

my 7 year old nephew and 4 year old niece both had a great time with it, but after two rounds, they were a bit bored with it. it's a game probably best in small doses, but those small doses can be a lot of fun, especially with animated kids.

title: Excellent game -- sure to become a Classic, but needs newer/better house rules and variations.
text:
A wonderful game -- sure to become a classic like Jenga.

This game requires a bit of physics know-how -- will it balance or will it topple over?

I would suggest you make your own rules. The 3 rule sets: beginner, medium, and advanced are just not well thought out.

I suggest that you make up your own rules like:
A. Removing pieces one by one.
B. What happens if some pieces fall off? Penalty points?
C. Timer for placing pieces.
D. What if you hang a piece and it touches the table?
etc. etc.

Nevertheless, the play pieces are well designed and the color-coding of the pieces are excellent.

title: An interesting game ...
text:
Suspend is a three-dimensional "hanging" game that harkens back to my youth, when most games involved plastic pieces or dice and where you often did things with the pieces, rather than jsut playing with hand-held electronic devices or game systems that are so prevalent now. The goal of this game is to hang rubber-tipped wire pieces from a stand that you construct, which is trickier than it sounds.

I played the game with two of my children, ages five and seven. (The recommended age is eight and up, but you can play with children younger than that, depending on the child and on the amount of help you give your child.) My seven year-old got proficient with the game rather quickly, while my five year old needed a little help, but did well.

We had fun for an afternoon, and as noted above, both of my kids rapidly got the "hang" of it (heh). But other than the first day, they haven't wanted to play Suspend again. I don't know if this is because they're a bit under the recommended age or if today's generation finds electronic toys more "fun". I, however, had a great time with the game and was even playing it by myself.

I applaud "Melissa and Doug" for making toys like this, where kids can learn real world skills, such eye-hand coordination and balance, while having fun doing it even though my brood didn't take to it as I had hoped. I'm keeping the toy until my children are a bit older, and I'll try to interest them again on a rainy or cold winter day. Four stars.

title: Super fun for older kids and adults
text: This game is so fun.  It really is geared toward older children an adults.  My 4 year old has tried to play and it is just too frustrating for him.  My 7 year old, however, is successful at it.  You start with a base and a tall stand and each person gets one bar of each color: red, blue, green, orange, yellow, and black.  You roll a little die that tells you which color bar you are supposed to play. This really keeps the game interesting and fun.  If you have already played a color and you roll the same color, you have to steal someone else's so that you make sure to play that color bar.  I like having these rules so it's not just a free-for-all.  We have yet to use all the pieces in a game because the bars usually come crashing down and we all bust of laughing.  Great for family game night for older kids and adults.

title: A Balancing Game that Can Balance out Your Overall Game Night
text:
This is one of those "add-on" games that we like to play at the end of a night of board games. It is relatively fast and quite challenging, but the trickiness of balancing the various rods gives even younger kids (5 or 6 and up probably) a chance to do just as well as the adults.

While the sets of rods are designed for playing with only four people, we have also found that just taking turns rolling the dice and playing whatever color comes up makes for a nice group activity for 5, 6, or even 7 players. This makes the game a little more like team rather than competitive play, as we work to see if we can build a structure using every single piece.

Quick change of pace activity for a game night, easy to learn, even if a little difficult to master. Recommended.

title: Fun game for the whole family
text:
WHY I BOUGHT IT:
I was looking for a game that I can play with both adults and children and doesn't require too much thinking.

WHAT YOU GET:
You will receive a plastic tube containing 24 rods, 4 frame rods, a die, a wooden base, a wooden connector.

HOW TO SET IT UP:
Setting up the game is very easy: you just need to stick 3 frame rods into the wooden base and then add a fourth one using the wooden connector.
Then you can distribute the metal rods, depending on how many people (up to 4) are going to play.

HOW TO PLAY:
The rules are simple (there are variants if you want to make the game more challenging): you first roll the die and take a rod of the corresponding color; you will then have to add the rod to the structure with caution, so that it doesn't collapse. If any rods fall, they become yours.
The first player that remains without rods wins.

THOUGHTS:
This game is very fun to play and it can entertain both adults and children.
I like that it doesn't take much space and is easy to carry around.
Moreover, the rods are very light, so you don't risk damaging your table.
The only, very minor thing, that could be improved is the fact that the black and blue colors on the die look very similar if you don't have a bright light source; after some time, you get used to it though.

So, rather than the staged complex structures you see, in reality, you tend to stay stuck at the starting point. Rarely, adding more than two consecutive pieces before complete collapse. The game just doesn't have a good success/failure ratio to maintain interest. Don't believe me? Try to find any videos of anyone playing Suspend correctly with no video edits or without starting with a lot of pieces already in a staged setup. Due to this lack of continuity, playability, the game just feels like a futile exercise. Rather than being fun, my thoughts go towards, what would I rather be doing, returning it or gifting, but who would want it?

I do believe the pieces could be redesigned to provide more hanging options for a greater success rate. Quality control of the game was good, no missing or defective pieces. The container is flimsy.

title: It is a fun game. It is similar to Jenga
text:
It is a fun game. It is similar to Jenga. When you first got Jenga, everyone wanted to play. It was a quick game and it was a novel idea that the whole family wanted to play multiple times. I assume, like Jenga, this game will run its course too.

It is a great game to have around for family reunions, or for family game night. My 7 year old is plenty old enough to play it and my 5 year old can play but he will knock the whole thing down, which he finds funny.

I do not like the limited instructions. If another player has to play a blue piece and the only one left to play is another persons piece, what happens if you just took the other players last piece, do they win? These types of decisions come up in this game and they are hard to decide when you are playing with children, so clearer rules would have been nice.

It is a fun game that I would pay no more than 15 dollars to own because there isn't a lot to it. I would give this as a gift, the container is a little small (if that matters to you).

12/24/13: Immediately upon contacting Amazon via the exchange option, they sent a new game with a guaranteed delivery date of 12/23, and told me that since the game I received was missing parts, I didn't need to send it back. The new game arrived, as promised, 12/23 (yesterday) and was complete, and as pictured.

I'm glad I went to the bother to have it replaced: turns out we weren't just missing the can and instructions, but also the die and several game pieces! All that said, this looks like a fun game for the cousins to play at our upcoming family gathering.

title: This is about the only game I have found where anyone from 6 years old to 99 years can enjoy! The parents break this game out be
text:
BUY THIS GAME NOW!

This is about the only game I have found where anyone from 6 years old to 99 years can enjoy! The parents break this game out before the kids do. The beginning may be a little slow, but the more you play the more advanced tricks you can pull off.

One thing I love about this game is that you never know who will win. It isn't based on experience. The more advanced players can pull some risky moves, but the can have their own moves turned against them easily.

Set up and tear down take seconds. And is a fun game to play on the patio after a mean. Put a tiny LED light underneath it to create a cool effect in the dark. A MUST BUY! Everyone in our family owns a set.

title: Good game; more about fun together, than about skill
text:
Neat idea for a balance game. Setup is easy.
The stand is sturdy; the upright posts of the stand connect together with a tiny cylinder wood piece. The upright piece is on an angle like is shown on the drawing of the package. The photo of the item might show the upright piece nearly vertical - it is not. It is on an angle, which is good because it allows you to balance pieces on the wood cylinder, which is an option in one of the game rules.

We'd make up our own rules:
Sometimes we'd just take turns balancing any piece we want to; then if it all falls, we just start over.
Or we'd try to make symmetrical balancing artwork with it for fun.
Or taking turns, the other person would choose with piece you would have to use next.

We'd play on the floor so the child could easily see and move all around the game while hanging pieces.

There is also a kid's version made out of plastic. The adult version is metal pieces.

title: Fun for adults, kids, AND great OT tool for my child with SPD
text:
We got this for my son's 5th birthday and I have to say it was a hit with the adults just as much as the kids! My kids were able to handle the rules and participate without assistance, which was great, and the different levels of difficulty made it fun when we played a game without them!

As an added bonus, this worked wonderfully as an OT exercise for my son with Sensory Processing Disorder who struggles with controlling his strength. He was able to work on using delicate touch and the fun of the game decreased his frustration levels dramatically. I would highly recommend this to parents with SPD kids!

The part I’m not happy about is the colors on the dice not matching the colors on the pieces, poor choice from the game makers. If your trying to teach colors you will confuse a younger child. I do recommend this game though, we’ve had fun with it as a family.

text:
We got this for our 4 year old for Christmas this year and we are all having fun!
Our 4 year old boy will even play it by himself.
Definitely challenging to try to balance out after he places a piece.
You can play cooperatively too.

After a couple disappointing puzzles from Melissa and Doug, the quality of this product is very nice!

Everything fits back into the original package for storing which is a definite plus for me.

I recommend this game.

Regarding the 1 star reviews that say this is very difficult; I disagree. The point of the game is to balance things and you may have to release your piece very slowly for it to balance but that is kind of the point.
It definitely requires some thought (a plus for us) and some care in your placement but our 4 year old boy has no problem hanging the pieces and even does pretty well with the yellow piece which is the hardest to balance.
Even my mom (who doesn't tend to like games) enjoys this one.
It may not be for everyone but it is not terribly difficult to learn, you can't just place and piece and let go.

title: WOW What Tension-filled FUN
text:
We played this every day since it arrived-all adults, all avid and critical game players. This was tremendously tense, exciting, and competitive with oohs and ahs and a "ghost" which spontaneously made things fall after the structure seemed stable. We had to create a 60 second rule and a next roller rule--you place and you are at risk for all things falling for 60 seconds or until someone else rolls. More than once the structure spontaneously jumped after a person rolled but before they played. We put the pieces in the draw pile.

BUY THIS GAME--you will have a great time.

title: This is a fun! fun! game for ages 8+.
text:
The concept of this game is fairly simple - keep adding rods to the basic form without touching another rod. Think Pick Up Sticks except in 3D.

The set contains dice, metal rods of various lengths, a wooden base and the starting rod which, once inserted, is tilted.

Divide the colored rods equally among the players. Each player gets the same amount of rods and the same amount of colors. The rods have different colors at the tip matching their length.

Toss the dice to show what color to play. To put the game very simply, keep balancing rods on other rods until you run out. The first person to run out of rods is the winner. The canister has more detailed instructions and different ways to play.

Simple, yes? Ha! More difficult than you think. It’s so much fun and it can involve the whole family OR make a drinking game out of it. The box didn’t mention that! ;-)

You’ll be glad to have this in your game closet. Very well made and easy to pack for a trip.

title: Fantastic, Fabulous Fascinating, Fun!!!
text: Played suspend with my husband and we had a blast.  It took a couple of tries to get the “hang” (sorry I couldn’t resist) of it.  Once we got into it we had about two hours worth of fun in one sitting.  We moved from beginner to intermediate game within that time.  The basic idea is to take turns hanging pieces with multiple grooves on each other trying not to knock any off.  The first one to get rid of all their pieces wins.  Definitely more difficult than it sounds.  It takes practice and as you add more pieces the structure is constantly shifting, adding to the challenge.  This makes for unique game play every time, but also, as other reviewers have noted, you get a really cool looking piece of modern art. My only negative is that the die that comes with the game (for intermediate game play) has colors that can be difficult to distinguish.  Having said that, the game was so much fun that I gave it 5 stars anyway.  Can’t wait to play again.

text:
This game is a gem. I first bought if from a local game store. When our family came to visit, the 10 and 12 year old kids loved it. They loved it so much that they probably played it 20-30 times over the weekend. Matter a fact, that is why I have ordered over amazon, they loved it so much that I had to give it to them so they could take it home. The price I paid on Amazon was half of what it cost in the local stores here.
Adults love it also.

Game play is great. The instructions allow you to vary the difficulty.

In simplicity, you roll the die "which selects with color piece you get to hang next". You hang it using one hand, if you make any fall than you get to add all those to your pile. Goal is to get rid of all of your pieces first. Every game is different and each one will get harder as players get more experience.

My 6 and 8 year old nephews have been staying with us for the past week and they play it at least once a day.

title: A big hit!
text: This is one game that puts kids and adults on an equal playing field.  No reading or knowledge is necessary, but it is challenging.  You'll find yourself holding your breath as you try to carefully hang another rod without knocking any down, especially when there are a lot of precariously balanced rods already perched.  Depending on which rules you're playing by, a game can last 10 minutes or an hour; I like that flexibility.  It's a simple, sturdy game that packs up easily in the tube, with no cardboard parts to bend and wear out.  Even men who don't play board games can't help liking this one.

title: A Nice Addition to Game Night with Kids
text:
So our family has younger kids, and trying to find games that even the 3 year old can play came sometimes be challenging. Our latest game is Jenga, which now that we have used Suspend has very similar qualities which is probably why they like this too. This game comes in a (flimsy) plastic tube that can somewhat be resealed, if you open it carefully on top. Definitely the container could have been made more durable. Then the pieces are made of medal, wood and a bit of plastic. The general goal of the game is to balance as many of the pieces as you can, but if any of them fall on your turn, you take the pieces. The person with the least pieces at the end wins.

I do like that they outline in the instructions the different ways of playing, from beginner to intermediate. In a lot of ways, you could make up your own versions of that depending on the number of people playing and the skill level. I also highly recommend that if you have kids older than 7 you allow them to play by themselves a few times as well. Gives them some strategies they can use once they join a group.

I think the price is right on this one, but again, I probably would have paid a bit more for a descent case for this.

title: Fun game and EXCELLENT customer service!
text: This is my first Melissa & Doug game and won't be my last!  I purchase new games and or puzzles for the Holidays when the family all home.  Saw this and it sounded fun.  Package arrived timely and undamaged.  When we opened there was one of the sticks that was bent and had a metal rough part.  I emailed them on Saturday December 30th and got a nice auto response which I expected as it was on the weekend and not during business hours.  To my surprise they sent an email on December 31st that was personal to me about my problem.  Very shocked as it was not only a Sunday but New Years Eve!  They asked that I call on Tuesday and would fix the problem.  Called Tuesday and they are sending new piece.  I would buy this game again as it is fun for all of us and I would especially buy again from Melissa & Doug as they have outstanding customer service and stand behind their products.

title: Awkward and not fun
text: I purchased Suspend as a Christmas gift for my 7 year old son. Our family plays Jenga a lot and we love it, so I thought this might be a variation on the stacking game idea. We played it 3 or 4 times at my request as my son knew after the first time that he didn't like it. I thought we should give it a chance. First, the game is actually quite large once it's set up. It might be better to try playing it on a linoleum floor rather than on a table top. Every time one of us would try to place a piece, all the wires would crash down. I don't think we stacked more than 5 or 6 pieces at a time before it would fall apart. The pieces didn't balance well, which I realize is part of the challenge, but it was awkward to the point of not being fun. Wanted to like it, but was disappointed and it was definitely a no-go as far as my son is concerned.

title: ... have one of these bought locally and it's been enjoyed by many people of all ages and skills
text: I have one of these bought locally and it's been enjoyed by many people of all ages and skills. The teenagers love it, which is unreal because it has no plugs, no computer memory, no joystick. The few people who haven't enjoyed it are typically the much older women in our circle of family and friends, but that's OK because it's sort of an engineering type hands-on game that this demographic typically wouldn't attempt or enjoy anyway. The game generally lasts only a short time, which works for those with a short attention span. It works on concentration, because you have to gently hang pieces off other pieces without knocking the whole thing down. The rules are simple, too. I am about to order several more to use as holiday gifts. Be sure to set it up on a stable table or counter, so people don't shake the base and cause it to fall when other players are hanging pieces. Fun game, well worth the small price.

title: Great game for all ages
text:
Purchased for a young teenager for Christmas to play with peers, as well as his younger siblings, and parents. Was looking for something that would be fair for any age group. Browsed through Amazon's games and this came up as a recommended item. I gave the gift on Christmas Eve when I had a house full of people. Suggesting he wait till he got home to play since you do need a solid/non wobbly surface to play on, I found him and his dad on the floor in the hallway playing. Later, after dinner was cleared off, the kitchen counter/peninsula became the hot spot where this game was continually being played by all....ages ranging from 7 to 51. Everyone having fun and even the youngest players feeling just as capable as the adults.

I have no idea what the rules are, since I was hosting and never got to sit and play, but they all seemed to have fun. I don't know if the included rules were actually being followed, but the house rules seemed to be accepted by all. The young players didn't seem to care about winning or losing either, and the adults didn't feel like they had to let the youngsters win.

It is similar to Jenga or Bandu, but way less noisy, messy when the tower falls. The pieces did not bounce all over the place and land on the floor as I thought they would. Very easy to clean up.

title: GREAT Game for 1-4 people
text:
I purchased this game for our grandchildren for Christmas. It is a game of strategy and balance. The manufacturer recommends it for ages 8+ and we found that age level approrpiate. The game is compactly packaged and easy to set up. All you need is a flat surface. Although there is a lot of luck in winning there is also skill learned in placing the metal, rubber tipped rods in a way that will not cause any other rods to fall. The rods are of different lengths with different colors and learning that the longer the rod, the easier it is to balance is the first lesson! Great fun for children and adults.

The game pieces are typical of Melissa and Doug products. They are well-made and sturdy.

The game was shipped quickly and packaged perfectly. I recommend this game and found the price on Amazon to be the best I could find at the time I made the purchase.

title: Slightly nerve-wracking, fun game!
text:
I first played this game with my 5-year-old son. It says on the package 8+, but with adult supervision (and a little help), this game can be adjusted down to play with children. He and I both had fun playing at the beginner level. I called my 7 year-old-daughter and her friend to come see it when we were finished, and they were excited to play. They are both smart girls, so I experimented and left them to their own devices with the game. They quit after a few minutes. So I would say that the recommended age of 8+ is pretty accurate - I'll try with my daughter again and I'm sure she'll love it.

The game play quickly makes you as anxious as a game of Jenga or Kerplunk. I thought it was neat to watch the way the whole structure changed with each piece, and rarely did the thing end up having pieces fall or touch the play surface during our game. To me, it felt like a combination of interacting with moving art, combined with an experiment in balance. I'm glad I got this game and would recommend it.

title: Great fun for all ages!
text:
I (mid-twenties) received this as a Christmas gift from my mother. I think she called it a "wildcard gift" - a risky pick that may or may not turn out to be fun. It turned out to be fun.

I've played this with younger people, with older people, friends, and strangers. The rules are very adaptable so it's quite fun to come up with house rules to change the game over time. We've played "infinite suspend" where we tried to keep the structure going for as long as possible; we've played it as a drinking game (with hilarious results, as proper play takes a good bit of hand-eye coordination); and we've played it according to every rule set that it shipped with.

I think the most striking aspect of Suspend, at least at first, was how beautiful the resulting structures can be. In the first game I played, we found ourselves snapping pictures of the game at various times because we were so struck with its appearance. And it's cheap, too! Get this game.

title: Interesting
text:
This is supposed to be a game where each player takes turns hanging a wire off of this wire contraption that is built during the course of the game. There are simple rules and the they are easy to read and easy to follow.

However, when my children and I pulled this out and began playing with it, we didn't follow the rules. It quickl became a game to see who could put up the most sticks before we toppled it. Or we tried to mess the other person up by putting the sticks on one spot so they could never get it balanced.

We had a great time playing it. We did not follow the rules and instead made up our own rules and games. We even started playing it by ourselves trying to see how we could balance the sticks as we built a new sculpture.

Very fun. Enjoy.

title: Great for tiddler fine-motor skills and spatial awareness

This is just what I was hoping for. Had been seeking out turn-taking balance games for my almost-3 to be able to play with alone as a free-form, open-ended activity, and to play with adults and peers.

I like the 3-dimensional shape-shifting aspect, and my partner and I enjoy giving each other challenges with how to hang them (touch at least two others, don't use the nooks, etc) when it's our turn. I assume since our kid is observing us playing that way, it won't be long before she wants to be challenged similarly.

title: Fun but needs some house rules to make it more of a game
text:
I'm an adult and I play this with adults. Its a fun 'activity' but the rules are kind of weak. It made the game much more interesting when players are trying to actively make the structure unstable which increases the risk of placing pieces in later turns.

We are experimenting with changing the rules a bit and it seems to be working well. With the new rules, you gain points for adding to the structure (same rules for how many points each piece is worth) and you lose points for everything that falls off. Play until the pieces run out or until someone gets to 15.

Still testing the point goal but it makes it more interesting.

title: Creative and Fun!
text: If you enjoy some what Jenga -- you will love this game. This is a similar game and game play but instead of deconstructing/reconstructing  and balance. this game is all about construction, strategy, and balance. Players on their  turn you will try to balance different lengths of metal on other metal which is all ready in play based on the color which they rolled on the dice. You will try to place your hooked metal pieces from your pile on the teetering metal madness which the other players have placed.  Whatever pieces you have fall over in your attempts become yours to evidently deal with. The first to get all of their pieces on the balancing metal structure wins.  This game is more exciting and strategic yet at the same time balanced than Jenga because even when you have one piece left you have to roll that color with your dice roll, if you don't have the color rolled then you have to take from another player's pile. Be careful and enjoy a great game for all ages.

title: The best game ever!
text:
This little game is a lot more than the size of the package. It's kind of like Pick-up-Sticks hung on a hook, and like Tip-It! in the way the tangle of pieces re-balances for every play. It has tension and drama like Jenga. It will never play the same way twice, thanks to the myriad of ways to hang the pieces and tangle them together.

I applaud the designers for their very simple yet very complex design. The pieces are simple rods of metal with rather precise notch-shaped bends, reminiscent of small coat hangers. A die roll and a color code determines the length, mass, and balance configuration of the next rod to be added to the tower. While most pieces have a symmetric hanging point, and thus balance perfectly, the addition of a second piece must create an imbalance, and therein is the fun aspect in the game: the tower is constantly shifting and tilting. What is more, the notches permit interlocking of pieces for the creative tower engineers, or hanging of the pieces in a precarious manner for the devious minds ready to sabotage the next player around the table. The colored rubber tips add a bit of traction to multiply the number of possibilities.

The rules are simple, making the game quick to set up and easy to explain. An obvious ending happens when the tangled tower crashed from the hook. The denouement can be slow-motion as single connections fail in sequence, which adds to the laughter. Even without rules, it is fun simply building a hanging structure solo. Young children can easily play this game. We have some crazy gamers in our family, who extended the rules to tally points for the number of notches that fall in a given turn, and to sometimes require a player to remove a color-coded stick from the tower instead of add one to it. Still further variations can be created by placing the base on a slope, using a shaky table, not using the dominant hand, securing the starting hook in an inverted position with a bit of tape, adding a rubber band to the hook, and so on. We have not yet exhausted our ideas after almost 2 years playing this game.

I am eager to see what is next! Four-notch sticks that have no symmetry? Angled sticks? Springs??

title: Simple, honest fun for all ages (no, really, all ages)!
text:
Have you ever wanted a game that both young children and fully grown drunk adults will have roaring laughing fits over? Have you ever wanted a game that's more likely to break your table than break the pieces?

Suspend is an extremely simple, quick to set up and quick to play game that everyone can love. Not just in a marketing sense, but genuinely; I've never met anyone, from young kids up to middle-aged adults, who didn't have fun playing this game.
Setup takes under a minute and the pieces are extremely durable, being mostly steel and wood with rubber tips. Gameplay is extremely simple as well, able to be learned in just a sentence or two.

Suspend: It's like Jenga, but in reverse.
Overall, a great game with solid construction, for a steal of a price.

title: Simple, versatile, and entertaining.
text:
This game is genius. It's highly portable, easy to set up, versatile, and simple to learn. It can be collaborative, competitive, or both. Best of all, it is one of the rare games that works equally well for school-aged kids and adults, making it a great choice for family games.
I'm sure it's not what Melissa & Doug intended, but it has immediately obviously appeal as a drinking game too — I gave this to my eight-year-old nephew for Christmas. All the adults loved it so much that we ended up "borrowing" it from him after he went home and playing about eight more rounds. We will be buying our own set!
One note - The game really is for eight and up. Most younger kids could play with the pieces and have fun, but wouldn't have the eye-hand coordination to be successful in a competitive game.

title: Fun Game, Terrible Packaging
text:
I actually got this game for my fiance and me to play while we were visiting family this holiday season. No difficult instructions to explain to others if they want to play and it is nice and compact and fits easily in a bag. But, that is where I had a lot of grief came about...the flimsy packaging.

1) The instructions hard to pull out of the plastic container, because it gets caught on the lip that holds the lid on, sort of.
2) The plastic got smushed and creased and dented after being placed in a tote bag, and the lid no longer wanted to stay on and it now won't sit on end.

I should see if a Pringles container is tall enough to contain all of the pieces, but it seems like this would be a better packaging solution, and much more durable. (at least that has a metal base and a cardboard tube cylinder)

The packaging issue aside, we love to play a round or two every so often. We spread out on the floor, try to keep the dog away and have at it. Our own personal added fun is to see if you can successfully lift the whole thing off the hook without losing pieces.

title: Fun Family Game
text: We bought the Suspend as gifts for three different families of our grandchildren - it was fun and challenging for children as well as adults.  The interesting twist to the game is actually helping someone else win by using one of their pieces if you don't have the right color in your supply.  There is suspense in Suspend in that if you don't successfully connect your piece and it causes other pieces to fall, you add to your number of pieces to balance which lessens your chances of winning.  It's a sturdy game.  We weren't quite sure if pieces could be connected in more than one notch.  Perhaps we didn't read the intstructions thoroughly enough.  At any rate - I would recommend it!

title: VERY fun game for young and old
text: I'm not sure why this is getting some bad reviews from people saying it is too hard or is not fun. I have children from 8 to 17 and we ALL love this game. This game is about balancing and using physics and logic to know where  to place the next piece. You roll the dice to determine which piece in your pile you must play and you have to hang it off of the pieces that are already in play. If you read the instructions and note which ways of hanging the piece are legal, there should be no problems with getting the whole structure to balance as you build it. My 8 year old picked it up in no time, and even my teenager plays it with her friends that come over. It has been a hit with everyone we have introduced it to, young and old.

title: Great for all ages
text:
This is one of our favorite games and it’s been good for our little kids.
We love to teach our children to problem solve, look at what’s happening around you, and how to think outside the box; this game does that simply. They have to look at the other pieces and predict what will happen when they place a rod in a certain place. They need to figure out where to put something even if there is no visible spot and sometimes you have to get creative as to where you put that big red one.
It has held up well so far. We have 4 little kids ranging in ages 3-8. Even our 3 year old (while needing to be on a team) has fun placing a piece and seeing what happens. Our 6 and 8 year old really get into it and often pick complicated placements.
While we love playing it with our kids, it’s also a lot of fun with adults. It doesn’t last too long, but it also isn’t too short. We can go through a few rounds before moving on to the next game and still want to come back to it. We play it with teenagers too and no one gets bored.
It is well made and has held up to our kids, however, you should still take care not to lose pieces especially the ones that secure and balance the base.
If you are looking for a new game, that isn’t a board game, this is a great choice for any family.

It is more 'diverse' than jenga, which is just blocks, all the same size, this game has different sized and colored pieces and multiple ways of playing the game.  The instructions are clear and concise and the tube can be used to store the game in time after time. title: Great addition to family game night!
text:
My kids are 2 and 5 years old, and we started family game night at the beginning of the year. After my husband and I were bored to tears with the little kid's games or the kids were frustrated with older games, I went in search of games for everyone. Surely there had to be games outside of hunger hippo! A game for everyone ages 2 to 200. I adore melissa and doug. Everything they make works so well for my family! I saw this and ordered it immediately.

My 2 year is very construction inclined and my 5 year old loves being good at any game or the best. They took to it immediately! Once the 2 year found out it could fall, he spent a couple rounds purposefully knocking it down but aftef that he did so well. The two of them will play it by themselves. They take turns and quietly play until it falls then there's tons of giggling and try agains. It is very easy to adapt the rules to fit your family. We try to make it a cooperative game and man oh man, I just can't get over how amazing this game is.

Its very sturdy and fits into the container well. I see this game helping with hand eye coordination, pincer grip, and being entertaining for years. We also added marbles to the game night. Unrelated but a suggestion.

title: It's made in America, so I didn't return it
text:
This is literally terrible. It's a great concept, and I was excited to get it, but make no mistake, it's impossible to play following the rules. You cannot put a piece up to start and have the second one not topple it. It's not possible. You must build a framework putting in two at a time, to build a very steady base, and then you can barely hang an offsetting piece. If the goals is to see if you can build a structure with all the pieces solo, or in tandem, then it's possible. But as a game and like the pictures show...not even close.

I support this company and they are Americans, so I didn't return it. If it was Chinese made, I would have.

title: BEST GAME EVER!!! (More or less)
text:
This game is AMAZING! I learned of it last summer as I walked by a table it was being played on. It immediately drew my attention, and I fell in love during my first game! Since then, I've ordered over a dozen of them as gifts for friends and family. I carry a set around whenever I'm going to a party or a bar, and it allways breaks the ice and draws in the curious! I'd say about 95% of the people I've played with love this game. It's easy to teach/learn, very durable/spilled-drink-resistant, fun for all ages, and caters to several different play-styles.

Things Melissa & Doug need to improve:
The case is flimsy plastic, and a few were broken during shipping. Sometimes the bottoms come loose. How about sturdy paper-board?
The wooden base could be a little larger to improve stability, and the holes could be tapered to keep the legs in place better. (Having the thing topple-over mid-game is fairly frustrating.)
Many players (especially the colorblind) have trouble discerning the different colors on the die/rods, especially in low light. A solid dot instead of the current concentric circles on the die's faces might help.
The rules don't explain how to determine who goes first. Best I've figured is to arrange the rods by length, calling Black 1, and Orange 6, and then rolling the die to see who gets the highest.

All in all, it's now one of my favorite games! Great job, Melissa & Doug!

title: Its addicting. Extremely addicting.
text:
[[VIDEOID:523fc92b5c67c0d62d3a1a7ad3eb6434]] Holy crap, never did I think this game would be so popular with my family. I got this game for my daughter and I, as we enjoy playing board games a lot. However most of my family loves video games, or simply enjoy watching.

Picture it. I'm slightly hungover christmas eve, trying to get the yummy, greasy breakfast ready when I'm thinking about giving the kid something early to preoccupy her eager "let's do something cool!" Mode. I had just gotten this game a few days before, intending to give it to her since I still hadn't opened it from the amazon package. I give it to her to open, while I grab some eggs for breakfast. I check out the specs, a bit confusing at first but easy enough to understand in my Spinny haze. And as we began, I mildly read the rules and just set it to an easy play mode. Roll the dice and place your piece to balance. Cool. I get to figure out how to balance then do what I need to without having to think too hard.

But oh boy....how did it lead to the only game any one else will play with us.

At first my brother came in, thought it was neat, and played a few pieces with the kid as I got breakfast going. He usually would play a round or two for jenga, but that was it. Never really wanted to play anything else. Then my other brother came in. Staring hard at it and wondering what it was. I explained and he got all kinds of giddy. I let him know I'd bring it out to the "hang out room" later, when I was fully done with what I had planned.

That's when hours of intense planning and semi hell broke loose.

One by one, I had family coming in to say hi, and somehow gained a gathering of how to properly play, and how we can play for our own rules during Christmas.

It. Lasted. HOURS. EVEN DAYS. 4 DAYS IN A ROW.

I highly reccomend this game, not only for growing your cognitive reasoning skills, but also how to make your friends and family twitch with anxiety and anticipation.

title: Nifty!
text:
A great, engaging game for (most) ages. This can be played cooperatively (let's see whether we can hang all of the pieces working together) or competitively (who will successfully hang all their pieces first?). And after you have all of the pieces hung, it's just as much fun to see if you can remove them one at a time without disrupting the entire sculpture. While it's recommended for 8 and up, a 3-year-old was able to hang pieces with a lot of help. Nevertheless, its challenging - and whimsical enough - to keep teens and adults engaged as well. Patience, concentration, a steady hand, and a little creativity are all key.

One minor critique - the packaging isn't very strong, and this is such a weird shaped bundle of pieces, you definitely need some sort of container to store it in.

Also, a wish - it would be great if they would come out with an extension pack with more odd shapes.

title: Needs a more durable container
text:
From the picture, I thought this toy would be packaged in a hard cardboard cylinder similar to what Tinkertoys or Lincoln Logs used to come in. Instead, it's in a flimsy clear-plastic cylinder, with the rules leaflet serving as the label. This isn't sturdy enough for the metal pieces and wood base, and when I received it, it was already damaged.

The game itself is fun, as long as you have space to set it up, and it's also fun to just make your own hanging sculptures. It's like a return to the simple games of yore like "Don't Break the Ice" or "Don't Spill the Beans." No reading is required; you can roll the color die, or just take turns placing pieces.

This would be five stars with better packaging. Melissa and Doug should have a talk with Ravensburger about making a box that lasts.

title: teaches thinking skills and basic physics
text: My nine-year old loves this -- She will spend hours creating different ways to balance the wires. To her mom and me, that means she's learning basic physics while using proactive thinking skills (about consequences and ripple-effects) at the same time.  It's also great because even though the game comes with a "rules" sheet outlining several ways to play, you can easily make up your own rules and just have fun.  Another benefit is you can have as many players as you want!  Set up is simple, and it stores quickly and easily, too.  The ONLY complaint is that the plastic tube to store the game is relatively cheap plastic (ours arrived broken at one end).  If that's the only complaint, you can still count this toy to be five stars.  I'd highly recommend this for the versatile, tangible learning it provides.  And who says it has to be limited to kids? I can see setting it out at a party and letting adults play, too!

title: A Nice Addition to Game Night with Kids
text:
So our family has younger kids, and trying to find games that even the 3 year old can play came sometimes be challenging. Our latest game is Jenga, which now that we have used Suspend has very similar qualities which is probably why they like this too. This game comes in a (flimsy) plastic tube that can somewhat be resealed, if you open it carefully on top. Definitely the container could have been made more durable. Then the pieces are made of medal, wood and a bit of plastic. The general goal of the game is to balance as many of the pieces as you can, but if any of them fall on your turn, you take the pieces. The person with the least pieces at the end wins.

I do like that they outline in the instructions the different ways of playing, from beginner to intermediate. In a lot of ways, you could make up your own versions of that depending on the number of people playing and the skill level. I also highly recommend that if you have kids older than 7 you allow them to play by themselves a few times as well. Gives them some strategies they can use once they join a group.

I think the price is right on this one, but again, I probably would have paid a bit more for a descent case for this.
